title: For Sale:  Collectors / Entrepreneurs
postcontent:
Ever hear of Hydra-Shok?                                                                  .

If you’re a shooter with any time in the sport - of course you have. And almost all of us have heard them mentioned throughout our shooting lives. And just about always, they're associated with the Federal Cartridge Company name.

Well, how about a deal on some original >> PRE-FEDERAL CARTRIDGE COMPANY << HYDRA-SHOK stuff!

I have two, partial boxes of it for sale. One in .357 magnum, and one in .38 Special (the original/original).

Here’s what I have…….

23 rounds of .357 Magnum. 
End flap marked, HYDRA-SHOK “125gr. SEMI-JKT COPPERHEAD”.  All cases stamped “HYDRA-SHOK 357 MAG".  They have nickel-plated cases and contain the semi-jacketed HYDRA-SHOK (center-post) Hollow-point bullet.

34 rounds of .38 Special. 
End flap marked, HYDRA-SHOK “146GR. SCORPION”.  All cases stamped “HYDRA-SHOK 38 SPL.  They have nickel-plated cases and contain the original HS lead (center-post) bullet.  There are also 12 empty cases included.

Both are in original, shelf-worn, 50ct-size red boxes and marked “HYDRA-SHOK CORP., WATKINS GLEN, NEW YORK 14891” along with Hydra-Shok proprietary information on the box backside. 

The name "FEDERAL" doesn't appear - anywhere.

I have no firm idea of what this stuff is worth, but one just has to look at comparative places like the auction sites showing lesser stuff going to and from collectors for $5 - $7 a round, says something.  Again, this is pre-Federal cartridge company stuff, with a very enviable history (if you’re a cartridge). These are the "Founding Fathers" of the the whole Hydra-Shok line.

Entrepreneurs ... at even $10 a pop (your shipping charges not included) you’re looking at $570. Plus you have the boxes . . . and don't we ALL know about boxes! 


$200 for everything / Pick-up in my area 

With FOID card please

title: For Sale:  Chinese SKS
postcontent:
Selling my Chinese SKS. It has Factory /26\ markings on it. From what I can narrow down, it was made in late 1956. 1956 was the first year factory 26 made the SKS. It has a six digit (all numeric) serial number. According to my research this means it is a late 1956 but I could be wrong. 

Has a Tapco T6 stock. I have not taken the original magazine off the gun in order to use the removable ones, I like the factory ten rounder just fine as it is extremely reliable. Have never had any feed problems. Not even once. If you buy this and want to convert it to use the notoriously unreliable removable magazines then be my guest. The stock is ready to take them. I just never felt the need to pull the factory one off. 

Comes with bayonet, cleaning kit and rod. I have the factory stock still packed in cosmoline, it is in rough shape and the upper handguard is broken in half (came that way when I got it from a local retailer). I even have the box it came in if you want that.

Some SKS info here. http://www.yooperj.com/SKS-24.htm

title: For Sale/Trade:  3 NICE GUNS: S.S. Kimber Ultra Raptor II, Ruger SR556 6.8 SPC., Custom Glock 27 Gen.4
postcontent:
I have 3 very nice guns for sale/trade including 2 handguns, & an AR-15 Variant rifle. I will start with the rifle 

Its a Ruger SR556 chambered in 6.8 SPC. It is in excellent condition, and I have shot it around 100 times. It comes with the Troy Iron Battle Sights, Troy quad rail, and Troy rail covers. It's a 2 stage gas piston driven setup, and it's all chrome plated. The bolt carrier assembly is also chrome plated. I have 4 25 round mags for it as well. I will sale it like this for $1,500.00. I also have an Eotech EXPS2-0 for it, a Primary Arms 3X long eye relief magnifier Gen. III, a Troy B.A.D. (Battery Assist Device), and about 200 rounds for it from polymer tips, BTHP (boat tail hollow point), soft point, and FMJ. The magnifier does not have a mount for it yet though. Also have the original A2 Birdcage flash suppressor, and on it is a Shark Muzzle Brake. I will sell it with all this for $2,200.

Next is the Custom Gen.4 Glock that has more money in the modification than the actual gun cost. Some people thinks its dumb, and swear by there stock Glock. This Glock isn't for those people. I feel like this Glock performs better than a factory Glock, and the money was well spent, and done right. This is a smooth shooting accurate subcompact Glock that is perfect for concealed carry, home defense, and personal defense. The trigger is super light, and its balanced to handle recoil better, and get back on target faster. First, it has Trijicon night sights. It has a Match-Grade KKM Precision barrel that was match fitted, and is extremely accurate. It has a Double spring tungsten guide rod that's 5X heavier than a factory guide rod, and 2X heavier than a Stainless Steel Guide rod. It helps greatly with muzzle flip, and recoil. I also installed a Zev Tech Fulcrum trigger, and trigger bar. I put a 6lb. Enhanced trigger spring in , a Ghost Evo 3.5 lb. connector, Lightning Strike Titanium polished safety plunger with reduced power safety spring, a 6 lb. firing pin spring, (also have a factory setting 5lb. And 4lb. Firing pin spring to reduce trigger weight more if desired), and a polished skeletonized firing pin with Marine Cups to make the trigger very smooth and crisp with a clean break at 4lbs. All the slip and grittiness is gone from the trigger with this setup. I have it setup for self defense with a 4lb. pull, and the pre-travel is slightly shorter than factory with the after travel virtually eliminated from the trigger. It can be adjusted to be lighter with the changing of some springs or heavier, and the pre travel and over travel can be adjusted to be a hair trigger to a long trigger pull. I put a Vickers Tactical mag release, and slide catch to help with the controls of the gun. If you know about these modifications you know it's not a cheap setup at all. I also have 3 mag all with +1 Pearce Grip Extensions, and a Minotour Comp-Tac IWB holster for it. I really want to trade this than sell it. I would need around $1,150.00 for it. I have close to $1,400.00 in it. If you want a polymer frame gun that performs like a high end 1911 this is your gun. If you just want a Glock this isn't for you. 

The last gun is much more simple. It needs no upgrades or extra parts. It's a Kimber Ultra Raptor in Stainless Steel. It has 3 Stainless Kimber mags, and a custom leather IWB holster. It's in excellent condition, and around 200 rounds put through it. Very beautiful gun, and is very accurate for a 3" barrel. I won't sale it for cash. It's trade only. I can trade it alone or in any combo with the other guns for the right deal.
